Looking at the code snippet and the link to the TypeScript SDK, I notice you're trying to set up a resource endpoint. Let me help explain how to use this tool.

The typical pattern for defining a resource should look like this:

```typescript
server.resource("resource-name", "/endpoint-path", async (uri, reqHandler) => {
    return {
        // Define your CRUD operations here
        get: async (req) => {
            // Handle GET requests
        },
        post: async (req) => {
            // Handle POST requests
        },
        put: async (req) => {
            // Handle PUT requests
        },
        delete: async (req) => {
            // Handle DELETE requests
        }
    };
});
```

Here's a more concrete example:

```typescript
server.resource("job-tags", "/job-tags", async (uri, reqHandler) => {
    return {
        get: async (req) => {
            // Return list of job tags
            return {
                status: 200,
                body: {
                    tags: ["javascript", "python", "react"]
                }
            };
        },
        post: async (req) => {
            // Create new job tag
            return {
                status: 201,
                body: {
                    message: "Tag created successfully"
                }
            };
        }
    };
});
```

Key points:
1. First argument is the resource name
2. Second argument is the endpoint path
3. Third argument is a callback function that returns an object with HTTP method handlers
4. Each handler (get, post, put, delete) can process requests and return responses

